COVID-19 in Newfoundland and Labrador

Dr.Â Amy Hurford

Memorial University of Newfoundland and Labrador, Canadian Network for Modelling Infectious Disease, Mathematics for Public Health, One Health Modelling Network for Emerging Infections

1. Are cases increasing?

Yes. That cases are increasing was stated by Dr.Â Fitzgerald in briefings on February 23 and March 1. Reported new cases have been increasing, as has the percentage of results that are positive (Figure 1).

Figure 1. Reported new cases (left) and percent positivity (right) from two public data sources. The data sources are the Department of Health and Community Services Public Advisories (aqua - dots: raw data; line: 14-day average) and the Newfoundland and Labrador COVID-19 Pandemic Update Hub (blue - astericks: raw data; line: 14-day average). In mid-January, hundreds of test results completed out-of-province were reported. For the Department of Health and Community Services Public Advisories data (manually curated) these cases were assigned to the day they were reported.


2. How should I understand my risk for becoming infected?

The risk of becoming infected depends on your vaccination status and other factors. An additional consideration is the total number of active cases (both reported and unreported; Figure 2 solid line). Currently, the total number of active cases is increasing.

Figure 2. Reported (symbols) and total (line) active cases as a percentage of the population of Newfoundland and Labrador. The number of unreported cases is estimated using the geometric mean method (see Methods). This method considers both the number of new cases, and the percentage of results that are positive. Reported active cases are calculated by assuming that reported new cases are active for the next 7 days. Colours denote two different data sources (as described in the Figure 1 caption).


3. How many cases are unreported?

From the Department of Health and Community Services Public Advisories, I estimate that since December 23 there were between 2.6 and 4.5 unreported cases per reported case (Figure 3; aqua line).

Figure 3. The number of unreported cases per reported case. The geometric mean method (coloured lines; described in the Methods) is compared to other estimates: K-12 RAT survey is rapid antigen testing of K-12 students performed on January 22 and 25 (see Hurford (2022)); CITF pre-Omicron is an estimate from the COVID Immunity Taskforce for Atlantic Canada prior to the establishment of the Omicron variant; Hospital admissions (low) and (high) are values given by Dr.Â Fitzgerald during media briefings from testing of all hospital admissions. Colours denote two different data sources (see Figure 1 caption).


4. Are there differences between Regional Health Authorities?

Figure 4. Reported (symbols) and total (line) active cases as a percentage of the population of each Regional Health Authority. Data are from the Newfoundland and Labrador COVID-19 Pandemic Update Hub as the public advisories do not report test numbers for each Regional Health Authority. See Figure 2 caption for additional details.


5. What is \(R\)?

For Newfoundland and Labrador, I estimate \(R\) = 1.1 secondary infections per infected person when considering data from the last 10 days. The doubling time is 18 days. For methodological details, see Methods.


6. What does the high percentage of positive tests mean?

High positivity occurs due to: (a) high infection prevalence; and/or (b) a testing bias towards identifying positive cases. In Newfoundland and Labrador, both factors likely have a role.

In Newfoundland and Labrador, asymptomatic contacts of cases should schedule a PCR test, and these individuals may frequently test positive. Rapid antigen tests became widely available in late January, which may have affected demand for PCR tests for individuals with COVID-like symptoms, who are not infected with COVID-19.


7. Does the increase in reported cases suggest that BA.2 is spreading?

The increase in reported cases can be explained by re-opening. These analyses cannot determine if the BA.2 variant is spreading.

Methods

Geometric mean method I estimate the prevalence of unreported cases 7 days ago as the geometric mean of the per capita reported new cases (14-day rolling average), and the proportion of tests that are positive (14-day rolling average; see Chui and Ndeffo-Mbah (2021) for details).

Estimating \(R\) I estimate \(R\) using the equation, and Omicron household generation interval estimates (mean and standard derviation), from Abbott et al.Â (2022). I estimate \(r\) by fitting an exponential function to the estimated total cases (reported and unreported) the using Department of Health and Community Services Public Advisories data over the last 10 days.
